Classes/PKMBerry.html.name: PKMBerry
Classes/PKMBerry.html.abstract: Berries are small fruits that can provide HP and status condition restoration, stat enhancement, and even damage negation when eaten by Pokémon. Check out Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMBerryFlavor.html.name: PKMBerryFlavor
Classes/PKMBerryFlavor.html.abstract: Flavors determine whether a Pokémon will benefit or suffer from eating a berry based on their nature. Check out Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMContestType.html.name: PKMContestType
Classes/PKMContestType.html.abstract: Contest types are categories judges used to weigh a Pokémon’s condition in Pokémon contests. Check out Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMContestEffect.html.name: PKMContestEffect
Classes/PKMContestEffect.html.abstract: Contest effects refer to the effects of moves when used in contests.

Classes/PKMSuperContestEffect.html.name: PKMSuperContestEffect
Classes/PKMSuperContestEffect.html.abstract: Super contest effects refer to the effects of moves when used in super contests.

Classes/PKMEncounterMethod.html.name: PKMEncounterMethod
Classes/PKMEncounterMethod.html.abstract: Methods by which the player might can encounter Pokémon in the wild, e.g., walking in tall grass. Check out Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMEvolutionTrigger.html.name: PKMEvolutionTrigger
Classes/PKMEvolutionTrigger.html.abstract: Evolution triggers are the events and conditions that cause a pokemon to evolve. Check out Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMGeneration.html.name: PKMGeneration
Classes/PKMGeneration.html.abstract: A generation is a grouping of the Pokémon games that separates them based on the Pokémon they include. In each generation, a new set of Pokémon, Moves, Abilities and Types that did not exist in the previous generation are released.

Classes/PKMPokedex.html.name: PKMPokedex
Classes/PKMPokedex.html.abstract: A Pokédex is a handheld electronic encyclopedia device; one which is capable of recording and retaining information of the various Pokémon in a given region with the exception of the national dex and some smaller dexes related to portions of a region. See Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMVersion.html.name: PKMVersion
Classes/PKMVersion.html.abstract: Versions of the games, e.g., Red, Blue or Yellow.

Classes/PKMVersionGroup.html.name: PKMVersionGroup
Classes/PKMVersionGroup.html.abstract: Version groups categorize highly similar versions of the games.

Classes/PKMItem.html.name: PKMItem
Classes/PKMItem.html.abstract: An item is an object in the games which the player can pick up, keep in their bag, and use in some manner. They have various uses, including healing, powering up, helping catch Pokémon, or to access a new area.

Classes/PKMItemAttribute.html.name: PKMItemAttribute
Classes/PKMItemAttribute.html.abstract: Item attributes define particular aspects of items, e.g. usable in battle or consumable.

Classes/PKMItemCategory.html.name: PKMItemCategory
Classes/PKMItemCategory.html.abstract: Item categories determine where items will be placed in the players bag.

Classes/PKMItemFlingEffect.html.name: PKMItemFlingEffect
Classes/PKMItemFlingEffect.html.abstract: The various effects of the move Fling when used with different items.

Classes/PKMItemPocket.html.name: PKMItemPocket
Classes/PKMItemPocket.html.abstract: Pockets within the players bag used for storing items by category.

Classes/PKMLocation.html.name: PKMLocation
Classes/PKMLocation.html.abstract: Locations that can be visited within the games. Locations make up sizable portions of regions, like cities or routes.

Classes/PKMLocationArea.html.name: PKMLocationArea
Classes/PKMLocationArea.html.abstract: Location areas are sections of areas, such as floors in a building or cave. Each area has its own set of possible Pokémon encounters.

Classes/PKMPalParkEncounterSpecies.html.name: PKMPalParkEncounterSpecies
Classes/PKMPalParkEncounterSpecies.html.abstract: Areas used for grouping Pokémon encounters in Pal Park. They’re like habitats that are specific to Pal Park.

Classes/PKMRegion.html.name: PKMRegion
Classes/PKMRegion.html.abstract: A region is an organized area of the Pokémon world. Most often, the main difference between regions is the species of Pokémon that can be encountered within them.

Classes/PKMMove.html.name: PKMMove
Classes/PKMMove.html.abstract: Moves are the skills of Pokémon in battle. In battle, a Pokémon uses one move each turn. Some moves (including those learned by Hidden Machine) can be used outside of battle as well, usually for the purpose of removing obstacles or exploring new areas.

Classes/PKMMoveAilment.html.name: PKMMoveAilment
Classes/PKMMoveAilment.html.abstract: Move Ailments are status conditions caused by moves used during battle. See Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMMoveBattleStyle.html.name: PKMMoveBattleStyle
Classes/PKMMoveBattleStyle.html.abstract: Styles of moves when used in the Battle Palace. See Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMMoveCategory.html.name: PKMMoveCategory
Classes/PKMMoveCategory.html.abstract: Very general categories that loosely group move effects.

Classes/PKMMoveDamageClass.html.name: PKMMoveDamageClass
Classes/PKMMoveDamageClass.html.abstract: Damage classes moves can have, e.g. physical, special, or non-damaging.

Classes/PKMMoveLearnMethod.html.name: PKMMoveLearnMethod
Classes/PKMMoveLearnMethod.html.abstract: Methods by which Pokémon can learn moves.

Classes/PKMMoveTarget.html.name: PKMMoveTarget
Classes/PKMMoveTarget.html.abstract: Targets moves can be directed at during battle. Targets can be Pokémon, environments or even other moves.

Classes/PKMAbility.html.name: PKMAbility
Classes/PKMAbility.html.abstract: Abilities provide passive effects for Pokémon in battle or in the overworld. Pokémon have mutiple possible abilities but can have only one ability at a time. Check out Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMCharacteristic.html.name: PKMCharacteristic
Classes/PKMCharacteristic.html.abstract: Characteristics indicate which stat contains a Pokémon’s highest IV. A Pokémon’s Characteristic is determined by the remainder of its highest IV divided by 5 (gene_modulo). Check out Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMEggGroup.html.name: PKMEggGroup
Classes/PKMEggGroup.html.abstract: Egg Groups are categories which determine which Pokémon are able to interbreed. Pokémon may belong to either one or two Egg Groups. Check out Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMGender.html.name: PKMGender
Classes/PKMGender.html.abstract: Genders were introduced in Generation II for the purposes of breeding Pokémon but can also result in visual differences or even different evolutionary lines. Check out Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMGrowthRate.html.name: PKMGrowthRate
Classes/PKMGrowthRate.html.abstract: Growth rates are the speed with which Pokémon gain levels through experience. Check out Bulbapedia ( http://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Experience ) for greater detail.

Classes/PKMNature.html.name: PKMNature
Classes/PKMNature.html.abstract: Natures influence how a Pokémon’s stats grow. See Bulbapedia ( http://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Nature ) for greater detail.

Classes/PKMPokeathlonStat.html.name: PKMPokeathlonStat
Classes/PKMPokeathlonStat.html.abstract: Pokeathlon Stats are different attributes of a Pokémon’s performance in Pokéathlons. In Pokéathlons, competitions happen on different courses; one for each of the different Pokéathlon stats. See Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMPokemon.html.name: PKMPokemon
Classes/PKMPokemon.html.abstract: Pokémon are the creatures that inhabit the world of the Pokémon games. They can be caught using Pokéballs and trained by battling with other Pokémon. See Bulbapedia for greater detail.

Classes/PKMPokemonColor.html.name: PKMPokemonColor
Classes/PKMPokemonColor.html.abstract: Colors used for sorting Pokémon in a Pokédex. The color listed in the Pokédex is usually the color most apparent or covering each Pokémon’s body. No orange category exists; Pokémon that are primarily orange are listed as red or brown.

Classes/PKMPokemonForm.html.name: PKMPokemonForm
Classes/PKMPokemonForm.html.abstract: Some Pokémon have the ability to take on different forms. At times, these differences are purely cosmetic and have no bearing on the difference in the Pokémon’s stats from another; however, several Pokémon differ in stats (other than HP), type, and Ability depending on their form.

Classes/PKMPokemonHabitat.html.name: PKMPokemonHabitat
Classes/PKMPokemonHabitat.html.abstract: Habitats are generally different terrain Pokémon can be found in but can also be areas designated for rare or legendary Pokémon.

Classes/PKMPokemonShape.html.name: PKMPokemonShape
Classes/PKMPokemonShape.html.abstract: Shapes used for sorting Pokémon in a Pokédex.

Classes/PKMPokemonSpecies.html.name: PKMPokemonSpecies
Classes/PKMPokemonSpecies.html.abstract: A Pokémon Species forms the basis for at least one Pokémon. Attributes of a Pokémon species are shared across all varieties of Pokémon within the species. A good example is Wormadam; Wormadam is the species which can be found in three different varieties, Wormadam-Trash, Wormadam-Sandy and Wormadam-Plant.

Classes/PKMStat.html.name: PKMStat
Classes/PKMStat.html.abstract: Stats determine certain aspects of battles. Each Pokémon has a value for each stat which grows as they gain levels and can be altered momentarily by effects in battles.

Classes/PKMType.html.name: PKMType
Classes/PKMType.html.abstract: Types are properties for Pokémon and their moves. Each type has three properties: which types of Pokémon it is super effective against, which types of Pokémon it is not very effective against, and which types of Pokémon it is completely ineffective against.

Classes/PKMLanguage.html.name: PKMLanguage
Classes/PKMLanguage.html.abstract: Languages for translations of API resource information.
